Initial inspection of the reads to identify and remove contaminants. Plotting of the negative controls composition.

Negative controls barplot:

library(phyloseq)
library(ggplot2)

neg_otutable <- read.csv("Negative_controls_otutable.csv", row.names = 1)
taxonomy <- read.csv("OTUs_Taxonomy.csv", header = TRUE, row.names = 1)
taxonomy <- as.matrix(taxonomy)

#create a phyloseq object
neg_otu = otu_table(neg_otutable, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
tax = tax_table(taxonomy)
neg_physeq1 <- phyloseq(neg_otu, tax)
neg_physeq2 = transform_sample_counts(neg_physeq1, function(x) x / sum(x) )
#order the barplots as you prefer and change palette
neg_layout <- c("N1C", "N2C", "N3C", "N4C", "N5C", "N6C", "N1M", "N3M", "N4M", "PCR_BLK_3",  "PCR_BLK_4")
neg_palette <- c("dodgerblue4", "red3", 
                 "green4", "#6A3D9A" , # purple
                 "#FF7F00", # orange
                 "deepskyblue3", "gold1",
                 "cadetblue2", "#FB9A99", # smooth pink
                 "darkseagreen", "#CAB2D6", # smooth purple
                 "#FDBF6F", # smooth orange
                 "sienna3", "khaki2", "maroon", 
                 "orchid", "darkorange4", "greenyellow",
                 "deeppink1", "navyblue", "tan", 
                 "darkolivegreen2", "steelblue4",
                 "darkturquoise", "green3", "yellow2", "brown")
neg_plot <- plot_bar(neg_physeq2, fill = "Family")+ 
  scale_fill_manual(values = neg_palette)
neg_plot$data$Sample <- factor(neg_plot$data$Sample, levels = neg_layout)
neg_plot

#Plot absolute abundances to visualize differencies in the number of reads among samples

  scale_fill_manual(values = neg_palette)

library(GUniFrac)
## Loading required package: vegan

#import original otutable with contaminants

#rarefy
otutable_reverse <- as.data.frame(t(otutable))
otutable_rarefied <- Rarefy(otutable_reverse, depth = 4000)
otu <- as.data.frame(otutable_rarefied$otu.tab.rff)
otutable <- as.data.frame(t(otu))
rm(otu, otutable_reverse, otutable_rarefied)

#remove empty rows
temp1 <- otutable[rowSums(otutable) > 0, ]
otutable <- temp1
rm(temp1)

#create a reduced otutable for plotting the heatmap
#select the first 20 OTUs:
otutable_reduced <- otutable[1:20,] #select the first 20 OTUs
#select specific OTUs (those present in the negative controls):
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU22",])
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU28",])
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU29",])
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU41",])
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU43",])

otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU87",])
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU97",])
otutable_reduced <- rbind(otutable_reduced, otutable["OTU124",])
otutable_reduced <- na.omit(otutable_reduced) #becouse some OTus were removed by the rarefaction process
#remove mitochondria
otutable_reduced <- as.data.frame(t(otutable_reduced))
otutable_reduced$OTU8 <- NULL
otutable_reduced$OTU17 <- NULL
otutable_reduced <- as.data.frame(t(otutable_reduced))

Rarefaction procedure of the filtered otu table:

library(GUniFrac)

#import the otutable without contaminants
otutable <- read.csv("Otutable_filtered.csv", row.names = 1)

#rarefy
otutable_reverse <- as.data.frame(t(otutable))
otutable_rarefied <- Rarefy(otutable_reverse, depth = 4000)
otu <- as.data.frame(otutable_rarefied$otu.tab.rff)
otutable <- as.data.frame(t(otu))
rm(otu, otutable_reverse, otutable_rarefied)
empty_row_removed <- otutable[which(rowSums(otutable) > 0), ]
otutable <- empty_row_removed
rm(empty_row_removed)

Staked barplot & heatmap- microbial groups composition:

library(phyloseq)
library(ggplot2)
library(vegan)

otutable <- read.csv("Otutable_rarefied.csv", row.names = 1)
taxonomy <- read.csv("OTUs_Taxonomy.csv", header = TRUE, row.names = 1)
taxonomy <- as.matrix(taxonomy)

names <- read.csv("Gropus_info_file.csv", row.names = 1)
row.names(names) <- names$Sample
v <- names$Groups
v <- as.vector(v)
colnames(otutable) <- v
temp1 <- t(otutable)
#merge rows with the same name
temp2 <- by(temp1, INDICES = row.names(temp1), FUN=colSums)
otutable <- as.data.frame(do.call(cbind,temp2))
rm(temp1, temp2, v)

#Staked barplot
collapsed <- otutable
collapsed[3,] <- colSums(x = collapsed[3:65,])
otutable_collapsed <- collapsed[1:3,]
rownames(otutable_collapsed)[3]<-"Others"
rm(collapsed)

layout1 <- c("CHB", "CSB", "MHB", "MSB", "CHA", "CSA", "MHA", "MSA")
layout2 <- c("CHB", "MHB", "CHA", "CSA", "CSB", "MSA", "MHA", "MSB") #jaccard beta diversity order
palette <- c("#FDBF6F", "sienna3", "slategray1")

otu = otu_table(otutable_collapsed, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
tax = tax_table(taxonomy)
physeq <- phyloseq(otu, tax)
physeq2 = transform_sample_counts(physeq, function(x) x / sum(x))
groups_plot <- plot_bar(physeq2, fill = "Family") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette)
groups_plot$data$Sample <- factor(groups_plot$data$Sample, levels = layout2)
groups_plot

# heatmap
library(gplots)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
library(RColorBrewer)

inverted_otutable <- t(otutable)
#trasform raw counts to proportions
data.prop <- inverted_otutable/rowSums(inverted_otutable)
coul <- colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(8, "YlOrBr"))(25)
#calculate dendrogram
data.dist <- vegdist(data.prop, method = "jaccard")
row.clus <- hclust(data.dist, "aver")
heatmap.2(data.prop[, 1:2], scale = "none", col = coul, 
          trace = "none", density.info = "none",
          Rowv = as.dendrogram(row.clus),
          dendrogram = c("row"))

Metadata wrangling (filtering out removed samples):

otutable <- read.csv("Otutable_rarefied.csv", row.names = 1)
metadata <- read.csv("Metadata_original.csv", row.names = 1, header = T)
samples <- colnames(otutable)
meta <- subset(metadata, select = samples)
rm(metadata, samples)
meta <- as.data.frame(t(meta))
write.csv(meta, file = "Metadata_filtered.csv")

PERMANOVA - adonis (samples before treatment):

library(vegan)

otutable <- read.csv("Otutable_rarefied.csv", row.names = 1)
meta <- read.csv("Metadata_filtered.csv", row.names = 1, header = T)
meta_before <- meta[which(meta$Treatment == "B"),]

#rename columns
names <- read.csv("Gropus_info_file.csv", row.names = 1)
row.names(names) <- names$Sample
v <- names$Groups
v <- as.vector(v)
colnames(otutable) <- v
rm(v)

#remove CHA
columns <- colnames(otutable)
count <- 0
for (i in columns){
  if (i == "CHA")
    count <- count +1
}
for (i in 1:count){
  otutable$CHA <- NULL
}

#remove CSA
columns <- colnames(otutable)
count <- 0
for (i in columns){
  if (i == "CSA")
    count <- count +1
}
for (i in 1:count){
  otutable$CSA <- NULL
}

#remove MHA
columns <- colnames(otutable)
count <- 0
for (i in columns){
  if (i == "MHA")
    count <- count +1
}
for (i in 1:count){
  otutable$MHA <- NULL
}

#remove MSA
columns <- colnames(otutable)
count <- 0
for (i in columns){
  if (i == "MSA")
    count <- count +1
}
for (i in 1:count){
  otutable$MSA <- NULL
}

Differencies in weight:

# import metadata meta
meta <- read.csv("Metadata_filtered.csv", row.names = 1)
meta$Aliivibrio <- otutable$OTU1/4000
meta$Mycoplasma <- otutable$OTU2/4000

#split the dataframe (before vs after treatment)
before <- meta[which(meta$Treatment == "B"),]

#split the dataframe (high Aliivibrio vs high Mycoplamsa)
high_vibrio <- before[which(before$Aliivibrio >= 0.8),]
high_myco <- before[which(before$Mycoplasma >= 0.8),]

#normality
shapiro.test(high_vibrio$Weight) # p-value = 0.05632 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  high_vibrio$Weight
## W = 0.9218, p-value = 0.05632
shapiro.test(high_myco$Weight) # p-value = 0.2448
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  high_myco$Weight
## W = 0.96265, p-value = 0.2448
#qqplots
qqnorm(high_vibrio$Weight, pch = 1, frame = FALSE, main = "Weight in fish with high Aliivibrio relative abundcance Q-Q Plot")

qqnorm(high_myco$Weight, pch = 1, frame = FALSE, main = "Weight in fish with high Mycoplasma relative abundcance Q-Q Plot")

#test if two samples have same variance (fisher's F test)
var.test(high_vibrio$Weight, high_myco$Weight) # p-value = 0.2795
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  high_vibrio$Weight and high_myco$Weight
## F = 1.4816, num df = 24, denom df = 36, p-value = 0.2795
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.7229601 3.2111960
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           1.481646
# Welch Two Sample t-test: (normality and equality of variance are respected, sample size different)
t.test(high_vibrio$Weight, high_myco$Weight) #  p-value = 0.000478 (they are differet!)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  high_vibrio$Weight and high_myco$Weight
## t = -3.7688, df = 44.685, p-value = 0.000478

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -31.29095  -9.49175
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  187.1600  207.5514
mean(high_vibrio$Weight) #187.16
## [1] 187.16
sd(high_vibrio$Weight) #22.41967
## [1] 22.41967
mean(high_myco$Weight) #207.5514
## [1] 207.5514
sd(high_myco$Weight) #18.41861
## [1] 18.41861

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

otutable <- read.csv("Otutable_rarefied.csv", row.names = 1)
otutable <- as.data.frame(t(otutable))
meta <- read.csv("Metadata_filtered.csv", row.names = 1)
meta$Aliivibrio <- otutable$OTU1/4000
meta$Mycoplasma <- otutable$OTU2/4000
Cts <- read.csv("Ct_values.csv", row.names = 1)
colnames(Cts) <- c("Sample", "Ct")
merged_meta <- merge(meta, Cts, by = "Sample")

Introduce a Ct values correction to each sample:

corrected ct value = ct value + (log2(a/m) * Aliivibrio relative abundance) a = Aliivibrio genus median 16S rRNA gene copy number (a = 12) m = Mycoplasma genus median 16S rRNA gene copy number (m = 2)

merged_meta$Ct_corr <- merged_meta$Ct + (merged_meta$Aliivibrio * 2.58)

chb <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "CHB"),]
csb <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "CSB"),]
mhb <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "MHB"),]
msb <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "MSB"),]
cha <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "CHA"),]
csa <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "CSA"),]
mha <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "MHA"),]
msa <- merged_meta[which(merged_meta$Groups == "MSA"),]

merged_meta %>%
  arrange(Ct) %>%
  mutate(Groups = factor(Groups, levels=c("CHB", "CSB", "MHB", "MSB", "CHA", "CSA", "MHA", "MSA"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Groups, y = Ct, fill= Groups)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.18) + 
  theme_bw() +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("slategray1", "skyblue3", "rosybrown1", "indianred3", "slategray1", "skyblue3", "rosybrown1", "indianred3"))

#normality
shapiro.test(merged_meta$Ct)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  merged_meta$Ct
## W = 0.98753, p-value = 0.4599
qqnorm(chb$Ct)

qqnorm(csb$Ct)

qqnorm(mhb$Ct)

qqnorm(msb$Ct)

qqnorm(cha$Ct)

qqnorm(csa$Ct)

qqnorm(mha$Ct)

qqnorm(msa$Ct)

#equality of variances
leveneTest(Ct~Groups, merged_meta)
#ANOVA + TukeyHSD
CT.aov <- aov(Ct~Groups, data = merged_meta)
summary(CT.aov)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## Groups       7  663.7   94.82   11.94 8.29e-11 ***
## Residuals   94  746.3    7.94                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
TukeyHSD(CT.aov) #multiple comparison anova
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = Ct ~ Groups, data = merged_meta)
## 
## $Groups
##               diff        lwr        upr     p adj
## CHB-CHA -0.4319028 -3.5761172  2.7123115 0.9998756
## CSA-CHA -2.2476923 -5.6122797  1.1168951 0.4410149

#repete the analysis with the Ct correction:

merged_meta %>%
  arrange(Ct_corr) %>%
  mutate(Groups = factor(Groups, levels=c("CHB", "CSB", "MHB", "MSB", "CHA", "CSA", "MHA", "MSA"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Groups, y = Ct_corr, fill= Groups)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.18) + 
  theme_bw() +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("slategray1", "skyblue3", "rosybrown1", "indianred3", "slategray1", "skyblue3", "rosybrown1", "indianred3"))

#normality
shapiro.test(merged_meta$Ct_corr) #not normal

qqnorm(csa$Ct_corr)

qqnorm(mha$Ct_corr)

qqnorm(msa$Ct_corr)

#equality of variances
leveneTest(Ct_corr~Groups, merged_meta)

                     p.adjust.method = 'BH') #multiple comparison anova
